        <br>
        <h3>How to get stronger/build more muscle?</h3>
        <p>1. Be Consistent</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Train at least twice a week or more</li>
            <li>- Stick to a plan that is suitable for you</li>
            <li>- Track your progress</li>
            <li>- Set Goals</li>
        </ul>
        <p>2. Progressive Overload</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Important if you want to continuously increase your strength</li>
            <li>- You should gradually increase the intensity of your workouts over time (Increase the weight or volume)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>3. Proper Nutrition</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Aim for 1.6-2.2 grams of protein per kilogram of bodyweight per day (Lean meats, protein powder, milk, eggs,
                etc.)</li>
            <li>- Drink plenty of water</li>
            <li>- Eat a balanceed diet of carbohydrates, protein and fats</li>
            <li>- Eat fruits and vegetables</li>
        </ul>
        <p>4. Optimize Rest Periods</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Sleep is crucial for muscle recovery (Aim for 7-9 hours of sleep per night)</li>
            <li>- Consider light activites (Walking, stretching)</li>
            <li>- Also optimize rest periods in between sets (Optimal rest times are 3-5 minutes)</li>
        </ul>
        <br>
        <h3>How to reduce the risk of injury?</h3>
        <p>1. Start with a warm up</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Dynamic Stretching (e.g. Arm circles, leg swings, high knees, lunges, etc.)</li>
            <li>- Start with some light cardio (e.g. light jogging, walking, stair climbs)</li>
            <li>- Start with some warm-up exercises that target the muscles you are working on (Start with lighter weight)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>2. Learn Proper Form</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Hire a trusted fitness trainer</li>
            <li>- Watch videos and teach yourself</li>
        </ul>
        <p>3. Listen to your body</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- If your body is sore or you're sick, then you should rest. Easy as that. "No pain, no gain" is not real. :3</li>
            <li>- Do not overdo yourself in the gym; focus on weight you can handle</li>
        </ul>
        <p>4. Stay hydrated</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- You will get better muscle function</li>
            <li>- Hydration helps the body have better bloodflow which helps deliver oxygen and nutrients to your muscles</li>
            <li>- You will feel less fatigued (increased fatigue can increase the risk of injury)</li>
        </ul>
        <br>
        <h3>How to structure a workout plan?</h3>
        <p>1. Measure Your Fitness Level</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Your Body Mass Index (BMI)</li>
            <li>- How many pushups can you do?</li>
            <li>- How long does it take to run/walk 1 mile (1.6 kilometers)</li>
            <li>- How well is your joint mobility?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>2. Think about your fitness goals</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Ask Yourself:</li>
            <li>- Am I training to lose weight?</li>
            <li>- Am I training to gain muscle?</li>
            <li>- Am I training to get stronger?</li>
            <li>- Am I training to run faster/longer?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>3. Make a balanced routine</p>
        <ul>
            <li>- Include aerobic activity throughout your week</li>
            <li>- Incorporate strength training</li>
            <li>- Include stretching exercises into your routine</li>
        </ul>
